        <div id="myDIV01">
            <h5>Garden waste can contaminate a landfill bin or recycling bin in several ways:</h5>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
                <li class="list-group-item">Mixing with other types of waste: If garden waste is mixed with other types of waste, such as food waste or plastic, it can contaminate the bin. This can happen if the waste is not sorted properly or if it is put in the wrong bin. </li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Carrying pests: Garden waste, such as leaves or branches, can carry pests such as insects or rodents. If the waste is not properly contained or if the bin is not securely closed, these pests can escape and spread to other areas. </li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Causing odours: Garden waste can also cause unpleasant odours, especially if it is left in the bin for an extended period of time. This can attract pests and make the bin less pleasant to use. </li>
                <li class="list-group-item">To prevent garden waste from contaminating the bin, it is important to properly sort and contain the waste. This may involve using green bins garden waste and food waste, or using composting methods to dispose of garden waste in a way that is safe and environmentally friendly.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
