        <p><button onclick="myFunction03()">Learn more/Hide</button></p>
        <div id="myDIV03">
            <li class="list-group-item">According to Sustainability Victoria, approximately 95% of clothing and textiles that are disposed of in the bin end up in landfill, where they can take hundreds of years to break down and contribute to greenhouse gas emissions. Furthermore, textile waste in landfill can also release harmful chemicals and pollutants into the environment, posing a risk to human health and the ecosystem.  </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
                E-waste can contaminate bins and landfills in several ways:
                <h6>Hazardous materials: Many electronic devices contain hazardous materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium, which can leach into the soil and groundwater if they are not disposed of properly.</h6>
                <h6>Space constraints: E-waste takes up a significant amount of space in landfills, which are already facing limited capacity.</h6>
                <h6>Missed recycling opportunities: When e-waste is disposed of in the general waste bin, it is missed as a potential resource for recycling and repurposing. </h6>
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
