    <div class="card mb-3" style="width: 50%; float: left; padding: 10px ">
        <h4 class="card-header">Soft Plastic Waste</h4>
        <image width="100%" src="~/Images/SoftPlasticWaste.png" style="padding-bottom:10px" />
        <p><button onclick="myFunction04()">Learn more/Hide</button></p>
        <div id="myDIV04">
            <li class="list-group-item">Soft plastics, such as plastic bags, food packaging, and cling wrap, can contaminate the recycling bin in Victoria, Australia if they are not disposed of properly. Soft plastics cannot be recycled in the same way as hard plastics, as they have a different chemical composition and can clog up recycling machinery. According to the Australian Packaging Covenant Organisation, soft plastics account for approximately 20% of the plastic packaging used in Australia, but only 3% are recycled. </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">If soft plastics are placed in the recycling bin, they can cause contamination of other materials, such as paper and cardboard, which reduces the quality of the recycled material and can make it difficult to recycle. Soft plastics can also pose a risk to workers in the recycling facility, as they can get caught in machinery and cause blockages. </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">Unfortunately, the REDcycle program which allows for the collection and recycling of soft plastics by providing dedicated bins at participating supermarkets was suspended. Therefore, under recent recycling policy in Victoria, all soft plastic is going to landfill bin. Victoria Government must find another proper way to dispose soft plastic.  </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">It is important to note that not all soft plastics can be recycled, and it is important to check the guidelines of your local recycling program or drop-off location to see which types of soft plastics are accepted. It is also important to ensure that soft plastics are clean and dry before they are placed in the recycling bin or dropped off for recycling.   </li>
        </div>
