            <li class="list-group-item">Construction waste can contaminate the waste stream in several ways. First, construction waste is often bulky and heavy, which can cause problems for waste management infrastructure. For example, construction waste can overload garbage trucks and other waste collection vehicles, making it more difficult and expensive to transport and dispose of waste. Overloading can also damage collection vehicles and can lead to accidents and safety issues for workers.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item">Second, construction waste can contain hazardous materials that pose a risk to public health and the environment. For example, construction waste may contain asbestos, lead, and other hazardous materials that can leach into the soil and groundwater if not properly disposed of. These hazardous materials can also pose a risk to waste management workers if they come into contact with them. </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">Third, construction waste can contaminate the recycling stream if not properly sorted and disposed of. Many construction materials, such as concrete, bricks, and wood, can be recycled or repurposed if they are separated from other waste streams. However, if construction waste is mixed in with other waste streams, it can make it more difficult and expensive to separate and recycle these materials. </li>
        </div>
